>My question is, if there are 3 letters (a,b,c) it can be arranged in 
>different ways like (abc,acb,bac,bca,cba,cab), likewise, what is the 
>total number of arranging all 26 letters (a-z) in jumbled order?
>
>Thanks for your time!

Hi,

It's in the last post. There are 26! permutations of the 26 letters of
the alphabet, which is just over 4.03 * 10^26 ways, or just over 403
septillion.

